es and the rising price of oil. Deindustrialization has yet to be reversed, and progress toward creating a modern economy remains limited.This book explores the vital role that active government policies can play in transforming African economies. Such policies pertain not just to industry. They traverse all economic sectors, including finance, information technology, and agriculture. These packages of learning, industrial, and technology (LIT) policies aim to bring vigorous and lasting growth to the region. This collection features case studies of LIT policies in action in many parts of the world, examining their risks and rewards and what they mean for Sub-Saharan Africa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEconomic developmentzAfrica. 0aIndustrial policyzAfrica. 0aIndustrial promotionzAfrica. 0aLearningxEconomic aspectszAfrica. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Economic Development.2bisacsh1 aAbebe, Girum, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCagé, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChang, Ha-Joon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffith-Jones, Stephany, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHosono, Akio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarwowski, Ewa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeipziger, Danny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoman, Akbar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoman, Akbar, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPrimi, Annalisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaefer, Florian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSh